Get instructions from qualified

essary to avoid them.


Swimming, the most popular
water sport, is also the one in
which the least amount of eau
tion is exercised. The expert
swimmer knows enough to re-
spect the basic dangers of this
sport; the inexpert swimmer
should have enough sense to OBJ
serve the experts precautions.
Probably the most important
rule about swimming is to never
swim alone. Also, never swim at
night, just after eating, or when
tired. If just these four rules
would be remembered by all
swimmers, deaths by drowning
would be reduced considerably.


Some of the hazards associated
with water sports are not dam
gerous but merely annoying.
Ear infections are a minor, but
persistent, problem among swim
mers, water skiers and skin div
ers. Called Swimmers ear" this
ailment until recently kept thou
sands of people out of the water
for several weeks each year.


The reason ear infections are
so common among water sports
enthusiasts is because the mois-
ture left from swimming pro-
vides an ideal environment for
the rapid growth of bacteria and
fungi.


Antibiotics and sulfa drugs
are of little help in preventing
or treating ear infections be-
cause the organisms usually be-
come resistant to these drugs
very quickly.


But a prescription medication
called VoSol, made by Wampole
Laboratories of Stamford, Conn,
has proved an effective germ
killer while avoiding the draw
backs of antibiotics. 1t can also

rington of Detroit are visiting
Miss Jimmy L. Arlington. They
will continue their vacation in
California.


Miss Arlington will go to Okla
homa and Texas before resuming
her teaching duties.


Leonard Caldwell, Jr.. son of
Mr.. and Mrs. Leonard Caldwell,
Sr., is on duty with the u. S. Army
at Fort Ord, Calf.


Mr.. and Mrs. ]. P. Middleton,
Yvonne, Elizabeth, James Ill and
Eric spent a wonderful time in
the East. They visited Niagra
Falls.


Mr.. and Mrs. S. T. Burton of
Houston are visiting Miss Shirley
Johnson. They will visit the
coast.


The Debonairs resumed meet
ings Saturday night with Mrs.
Demetra Vann presiding.


Your reporter is enjoying the
weekend in San Diego, Calf.

Kay Summey, II, was to be
caught in the act of placing a
political poster on one of Arizona
Public Service Company's power
poles.


Jim Ripley, utility lineman,
joins with his fellow workers
urging candidates and their
helpers to refrain from attaching
posters to power poles as they
can cause linemen to fall and
suffer serious injuries.


In a special appeal to all can
didates of both political parties,
w. S. Mcfarland, Arizona Public
Service Company's safety super
visor, asked them and their
helpers not to tack or nail posters
on utility poles.


mails and tackS used to fasten
the signs create a safety hazard
for our linemen,'' Mcfarland
explained. He estimated that
about six company linemen are
injured each year from falls
which are usually caused by
foreign metal objects either
embedded in or attached to power
poles.


"For the safety of our linemen
we have given our people in
structions to remove all posters
from poles as soon as they are
spotted" the utility safety
spokesman said.


IL know these posters cost
money and the candidates
naturally want to gain as much
benefit from them as possible.
But, posters removed from power
poles won't win votes" Nc
Farland said.

Patrick w. (PaD O'Reilly,
Phoenix attorney and former
member of the State Legislature,
has announced his candidacy for
the Democratic nomination for
Attorney General.


O'Reilly, who served on the
Judiciary Committee of the House
of Representatives during the
22nd Legislature, has practiced
law in the Arizona courts for
Is years. He is the senior
partner of the law firm O'Reilly,
Pollock. Murphy & Pizzo.


A member of the House
Judiciary Committee. he played
major role in the revision and
codification of the laws of Ari-
iona during the third special
session of that legislature.


A native of Choctaw County,
Oklahoma, OReilly has lived in
Arizona for 33 of the 80 years
of his life. He graduated from
Wickenburg High School, attended
the University of New Mexico
and received his law degree from
the University of Arizona.


OReilly served three years in
the U. S. Navy during World War
II, and he is a member of the
Glendale American Legion Post
